---
/**
 * Hub for the benefit and retirement calculators.
 *
 * The organising idea is that two completely different rules govern this whole
 * area, and confusing them is the usual mistake: Social Security and SSDI turn
 * on a combined-income formula, disability policies turn on who paid the
 * premium. Neither has anything to do with the size of the benefit.
 */
import Base from '../../layouts/Base.astro';
import { BENEFIT_PAGES } from '../../lib/benefits-copy';
import { statesTaxingSocialSecurity } from '../../lib/household';
import { states } from '../../data/states';

const ssStates = statesTaxingSocialSecurity();
---

<Base
  title="Benefit and retirement tax calculators (2026) — SSDI, disability, Social Security"
  description="Calculators for how SSDI, short- and long-term disability, Social Security and 401(k) withdrawals are taxed in 2026 — separately and together."
>
  <section class="hero">
    <p class="hero-label">2026 tax year</p>
    <h1>Benefits and retirement</h1>
    <p class="tagline">Benefit income is taxed by rules that look nothing like the rules for wages.</p>
  </section>

  <p>
    Two rules govern almost everything here, and they have nothing in common. Social Security and SSDI
    are taxed on a <strong>combined-income formula</strong> — half the benefit plus your other income,
    tested against a threshold, and never more than 85% of the benefit taxable however high your income
    goes. Disability policies are taxed on a <strong>premium question</strong> — who paid for the policy,
    and whether the money that paid for it had already been taxed.
  </p>
  <p>
    Neither rule has anything to do with how large the benefit is. Both are usually got wrong in the same
    direction, which is why people are surprised in April rather than pleased.
  </p>

  <h2>Calculators</h2>
  <dl class="rule-list">
    {BENEFIT_PAGES.map((p) => (
      <>
        <dt><a href={`/benefits-tax-calculator/${p.slug}/`}>{p.h1}</a></dt>
        <dd>{p.tagline}</dd>
      </>
    ))}
  </dl>

  <div class="callout">
    <strong>The interaction that catches people</strong>
    <p>
      A benefit can become taxable without the benefit changing. The Social Security formula counts your
      whole household's income, so a spouse taking on freelance work — or an employer-paid disability
      policy starting — can make an SSDI benefit taxable that was tax-free the year before. The
      <a href="/">household calculator</a> models everyone at once for exactly that reason.
    </p>
  </div>

  <h2>The {ssStates.length} states that tax Social Security</h2>
  <p>Everywhere else leaves it alone entirely, whatever your income:</p>
  <ul class="link-columns">
    {ssStates.map((c) => <li>{states[c].name}</li>)}
  </ul>

  <h2>Related</h2>
  <ul class="link-columns">
    <li><a href="/">Household calculator — everyone and everything at once</a></li>
    <li><a href="/1099-tax-calculator/">1099 taxes by state</a></li>
    <li><a href="/paycheck-calculator/">Paycheck calculator</a></li>
    <li><a href="/quarterly-tax-calculator/">Quarterly payments</a></li>
  </ul>

  <p class="disclaimer">
    General information about how these benefits are taxed, not tax advice. Check with a tax professional
    before relying on any figure here.
  </p>
</Base>
